DURBAN - The Department of Forestry, Fisheries and the Environment Minister Barbara Creecy has set the record straight on the disposal of 1 500 tons of toxic chemicals off St Helena Bay by the vessel NS Qingdao. The vessel had a chemical reaction after its cargo came into contact with rainwater while discharging the cargo in the port of Durban. Concentrated toxic fumes were released into the atmosphere. The vessel was anchored at St Helena Bay. Creecy was responding to a parliamentary written question by the DA’s Cheryl Phillips, who wanted to know the names of the chemicals that were dumped and the measures the department was taking to reduce the toxicity of the dumped chemicals. Prior to the parliamentary written question, the DA’s Dave Bryant and Chris Hunsinger had called on Creecy and the South African Maritime Safety Authority to account to the parliamentary portfolio committees on the environment and transport regarding how permission was granted and whether the potentially devastating consequences of the dumping have been properly investigated. Responding to the parliamentary question, Creecy said the constituents of the chemicals disposed of to avert a serious environmental disaster (and remarks) were: In total, there were 1 684 tons of chemicals left on the vessel. Creecy further explained that in order to reduce the concentration of the chemicals, the following methodology was implemented: Moreover, the following monitoring was conducted: Daily News